Delta Lloyd, ING, Umicore, Unilever: Benelux Equity Preview

-- B y   J o h n   M a r t e n s   a n d   F r e d   P a l s
-- 
2011-08-04T04:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-03/delta-lloyd-ing-umicore-unilever-benelux-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Benelux markets. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are from the previous close.  The  AEX-Index (AEX)  in Amsterdam declined 2.9 percent to 310.69.
 Belgium ’s Bel20 Index fell 1.7 percent to 2,291.11. Luxembourg’s
LuxX Index lost 2.2 percent to 1,278.14.  Dutch stocks:  Delta Lloyd NV (DL)  : The Dutch insurer in which Aviva
Plc holds a 42 percent stake may report a first-half net loss of
369 million euros ($528 million), according to the average of
four analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg. Delta Lloyd shares
retreated 3.2 percent to 14.09 euros.  ING Groep NV (INGA)  : The biggest Dutch financial-
services company may say second-quarter net income rose to 1.21
billion euros, according to the average estimate in a Bloomberg
survey of 10 analysts, from 1.09 billion euros a year earlier.
The shares dropped 4.4 percent to 6.82 euros.  Unilever (UNA NA): The world’s second-largest maker of
 consumer goods  may say underlying sales growth accelerated to
5.8 percent in the second quarter, based on the median estimate
of 10 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News. The shares declined
1.5 percent to 22.10 euros.  Wereldhave NV (WHA)  : The Dutch property investor may
report second-quarter earnings excluding some items of 1.27
euros a share, according to the average estimate in a Bloomberg
survey of two analysts. Wereldhave decreased 0.9 percent to
62.10 euros.  Belgian stocks:  RHJ International (RHJI)  SA: The owner of U.K. wealth
manager Kleinwort Benson Group Plc said it will recover about
20.5 million euros from loans granted to its insolvent
subsidiary Honsel AG. RHJ retreated 0.9 percent to 4.55 euros.  Umicore (UMI)  SA: The Belgian maker of automotive
catalysts may say first-half net income rose to 156 million
euros, according to the average of six analyst estimates
compiled by Bloomberg, from 126.9 million euros a year earlier.
The shares lost 4.7 percent to 32.59 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
